{|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image=[[File:Design A-150.jpg|250px|alt=A large ship sails toward the reader, while four guns in two turrets point at about a 45-degree angle at something off in the distance]] |Ship caption=An artist's interpretation of a A-150-class battleship by Richard Allison. }} {{Infobox ship class overview |Name= A-150 |Builders= |Operators={{navy|Empire of Japan}} |Class before={{sclass-|Yamato|battleship|4}} |Class after= |Subclasses= |Cost= |Built range= |In service range= |In commission range= |Total ships building= |Total ships planned=2 |Total ships completed=0 |Total ships cancelled=2 |Total ships active= |Total ships laid up= |Total ships lost= |Total ships retired= |Total ships preserved= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship type=[[Battleship]] |Ship displacement=Approximately {{convert|70000|LT|ST t|lk=in}}<ref>Breyer (1973), p. 330</ref> |Ship length= {{Convert|263.0|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} (est.) |Ship beam= {{Convert|38.9|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} (est.) |Ship height= |Ship draft= |Ship depth= |Ship hold depth= |Ship decks= |Ship deck clearance= |Ship ramps= |Ship ice class= |Ship power= |Ship propulsion=Unknown |Ship range= |Ship endurance= |Ship boats= |Ship complement= |Ship crew= |Ship time to activate= |Ship sensors= |Ship EW= |Ship armament=*6 × {{convert|510|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}/45 [[Caliber#Caliber as measurement of length|caliber]] guns (3 × 2)<ref name=510mm/> *"Many"&nbsp;{{convert|100|mm|in|abbr=on}}/65 caliber guns<ref name=Garzke85/> |Ship armor=Possibly a {{convert|460|mm|in|abbr=on}} [[belt armor|side belt]]; nothing more is given in sources<ref name=Garzke86>Garzke and Dulin (1985), p. 86</ref><ref name="Conway's"/> |Ship aircraft= |Ship aircraft facilities= |Ship notes= }} |} '''Design A-150''', also known as the '''''Super Yamato'' class''',<ref group=A>Although called the "Super Yamato class" by some, Design A-150 was an entirely new design that derived little from the design of the {{sclass-|Yamato|battleship|2}}s. See: Garzke and Dulin, p. 85</ref> was an [[Empire of Japan|Imperial Japanese]] plan for a [[ship class|class]] of [[battleship]]s. Begun in 1938–39, the design was mostly complete by 1941. However, so that a demand for other types of warships could be met, all work on Design A-150 was halted and no [[keel]]s were laid. Authors William H. Garzke and Robert O. Dulin have argued that Design A-150 would have been the "most powerful battleships in history" because of the massive size of their main battery of six {{convert|510|mm|in|abbr=on}} guns as well as numerous smaller caliber weapons.<ref name=Garzke85/>
==Design==
===Background=== Initial plans for the A-150 battleships called for eight or nine {{convert|510|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} guns in double or triple turrets. The successful construction of a {{convert|480|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} gun in 1920–1921 made the Japanese confident that a {{convert|510|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} could be built. In addition, a top speed of {{convert|30|kn|lk=in}} was desired so that the class would be faster than the United States' {{convert|27|kn|mph km/h|abbr=on}} {{sclass-|North Carolina|battleship|1}}s. However, these grand specifications were curtailed when tests culminated in a ship that had a [[Displacement (ship)|displacement]] of some 90,000&nbsp;tons; it was felt that ships of this size would be "too large and too expensive".<ref name=Garzke85>Garzke and Dulin (1985), p. 85</ref>
===Specifications=== Initial design studies were undertaken after the completion of plans for the {{sclass-|Yamato|battleship|4}} (1938–39); they focused on a ship with a displacement nearer to that of the ''Yamato''s.<ref name=Gnmnjbbbhvgyiknjbhbvvttfghvbytvcyyvctvftarzke85-86>Garzke and Dulin (1985), pp. 85–86</ref> As the Japanese expected that the Americans would be able to obtain the true characteristics of that class (namely the principal armament of {{convert|460|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}), the use of 510&nbsp;mm guns was vital to keep with Japan's policy of individual ships' superiority over their American counterparts; the A-150s were meant to counter [[Montana-class battleship|the United States' reply]] to the ''Yamato''s.<ref name=Garzke85/>
Plans were "essentially completed" sometime in 1941;<ref name="Gnmnjbbbhvgyiknjbhbvvttfghvbytvcyyvctvftarzke85-86" /> however, similar to the fate of documents relating to the ''Yamato'' class,<ref>Muir (1990), p. 485</ref><ref>Skulski (1989), p. 8</ref> most papers and all plans relating to the class were destroyed at the end of the war, meaning that the full specifications of the ships are not known.<ref name=Garzke85/> It is known the ships would have had greater firepower than the ''Yamato'' class: a main battery of six 510&nbsp;mm (20.1&nbsp;inch) guns in three twin [[gun turret|turrets]] and a secondary armament of "many" {{convert|100|mm|in|abbr=on}}/65 caliber guns.<ref name="Gnmnjbbbhvgyiknjbhbvvttfghvbytvcyyvctvftarzke85-86" /> The displacement was to be similar to the ''Yamato'' class, which was around 60,000–70,000 [[metric ton|tonnes]].<ref name="Gnmnjbbbhvgyiknjbhbvvttfghvbytvcyyvctvftarzke85-86" /> The side armor [[Belt armor|belt]] was probably going to be {{convert|460|mm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name="Conway's">Gardiner and Chesneau (1980), p. 178</ref> This was so large that steel mills in Japan were incapable of manufacturing it; instead, "double [[strake]]s of armor plates" were going to be used, which would have been much less effective than just one single plate.<ref name="Gnmnjbbbhvgyiknjbhbvvttfghvbytvcyyvctvftarzke85-86" />
===Armament=== Although details of the smaller armament planned for the ships are not given in sources, a main battery of six {{convert|510|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}/45 [[caliber#Caliber as measurement of length|caliber]] guns in dual [[gun turret|turrets]] was definitely planned. These would have been the largest ever fitted to a [[capital ship]], dwarfing the {{convert|460|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} guns mounted on the ''Yamato'' class.<ref>Garzke and Dulin (1985), pp. 85 and 88</ref> By 1941, one—possibly two—of the 510&nbsp;mm guns were being constructed at the [[Kure Naval Arsenal]] and detailed designs of the turrets that would hold the guns were drawn up. The turrets would have weighed {{convert|2780|t|LT|lk=out}} and [[:wikt:train#Verb|trained]] at {{formatnum:2}}° per second through a range of {{formatnum:120}}° to port or starboard. The guns themselves could have fired at a maximum rate of 1 to 1.5 rounds per minute and be [[Gun laying|elevated]] from {{formatnum:-5}}° to {{formatnum:45}}°, with the elevation rate being {{formatnum:10}}° per second. They would have weighed {{convert|227|t|LT|abbr=on}} and would have been {{convert|23.56|m|in|abbr=on}} long. The [[gauge (bore diameter)|bore]] length was to have been around {{convert|22.84|m|in|abbr=on}}. The [[armor-piercing shell|armor-piercing]] ammunition would have weighed between 1900 and 2000&nbsp;kg (4190–4409&nbsp;lbs), while the [[Shell (projectile)#High-explosive|high explosive]] rounds would have been {{convert|1858|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=510mm>{{cite web | last=DiGiulian | first=Tony | title=51 cm/45 (20.1") "A" Type 98 (?) | url=http://navweaps.com/Weapons/WNJAP_20-45.htm | publisher=Navweaps | date=9 October 2006 | accessdate=5 November 2009}}</ref>
A secondary battery of "many" {{convert|100|mm|in|abbr=on}}/65 caliber guns was being considered, although this was not final. This design was the best [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft]] gun produced by Japan during the Second World War.<ref name=10cm>{{cite web | last=DiGiulian | first=Tony | title=10 cm/65 (3.9") Type 98 | url=http://navweaps.com/Weapons/WNJAP_39-65_t98.htm | publisher=Navweaps | date=9 October 2006 | accessdate=5 November 2009}}</ref> Overall, the weapons compared very well with other contemporary weapons. The key advantages that made it so successful—the "high muzzle velocity and a fast rate of fire"—resulted in a short 350–400-round service life. In anti-aircraft defense, their ceiling at {{formatnum:90}}° was {{convert|13000|m|ft|abbr=on}}, although the effective range was {{convert|11000|m|ft|abbr=on}}. They were able to fire 15–21 rounds per minute.<ref name=10cm/>
In ''Battleships: Axis and Neutral Battleships in World War II'', authors William H. Garzke and Robert O. Dulin argued that Design A-150 would have been the "most powerful battleships in history"<ref name=Garzke85/> because of the titanic main armament and the use of a dual purpose secondary battery.<ref name=Garzke85/>
==Construction== With war on the horizon in early 1941, all design work was diverted from battleships—even though the A-150s' design was virtually complete—so that a demand for "[[aircraft carrier]]s, [[cruiser]]s, and smaller ships"<ref name=Garzke85/> could be met. Even though no work was being done on them, two ships of Design A-150, provisionally designated as Warships Number 798 and 799, were projected in a 1942 building program. 798 was to be built in the same dock as {{Ship|Japanese aircraft carrier|Shinano||2}}, while 799 was to be built in [[Kure]] in the same dock as {{Ship|Japanese battleship|Yamato||2}} after the fourth ship in the class, Warship Number 111, was [[ship naming and launching|launched]]. Both of the ships' [[keel]]s were supposed to be laid in late 1941 or early 1942, launched in 1944/45, and finished in 1946/47. However, the war's turn against the Japanese after the [[Battle of Midway]] meant that the need for ships other than battleships never abated.<ref name="Gnmnjbbbhvgyiknjbhbvvttfghvbytvcyyvctvftarzke85-86" />
==See also== *[[H-class battleship proposals]] - A German battleship of a similar size and same fate. *[[Montana-class battleship]] - A U.S. battleship of a similar size and same fate.
